Our Christmas Tablescape!🎄
Last week, I got to participate in a women’s Christmas event with my Bible study group.  It’s one of those events where all the ladies decorate the table that they sit at. Our Bible study group had two tables to decorate. We decided to do one called “In the Beginning“ and one called “In the End“. 
Since Revelation is my favorite book right now, I was excited when my Bible study leader asked me to head up the decorating for the “In the End” table. 👏🏼 
In Revelation, it starts with the tribulation and talks about the seven seals on the scroll that are broken, the seven trumpets, and seven bowls of wrath poured out.  So to represent that, we used 7 golden trumpet candlesticks, 7 golden bowls (we mostly got from Goodwill and used rub n buff on them 😂) and a scroll. Revelation also talks about when Jesus comes back to get His bride, the body of believers, for the Marriage Supper of the Lamb. So we added some wedding elements to our tablescape like the wedding invitation, diamond ring napkins rings, and veils on the backs of the chairs.  It was so fun to create this tablescape with the sweet ladies in my Bible study!! It was a wonderful night to remember our Savior who came to earth as a baby, and who will one day (soon) come again as our Bridegroom!🙌🏼

Mom and I talked about this recipe a few weeks before she passed away (2009.) She said that one time she made some of these and took them to work. (She was a secretary at a church.) And when a needy person would come to the church for help, she would give them a loaf of poppy seed bread to take home with them.
She thought is was such a simple way to show someone you loved them.
Now, when Mom would make these, she would remove them from the pan, wrap them in plastic wrap, and tie them up with jute string.

She would usually attach something cute to it, like a tag with a scripture on it that she had made on her computer, or a small type of flower or leaf. She was great at “embellishing” a gift.

I think the thing I remember most about my mom is how much she was always doing for others. ❤️. It was her “recipe for living.” 

RECIPE FOR LIVING:
I shall pass this way but once.
Any good thing that I can do,
Any kindness I can show,
Let me do it now.
Let me not defer it or neglect it.
For I shall not pass this way again.

(This is a poem that Mom kept on our refrigerator when I was growing up. She also cross-stitched it and hung it on the wall in a frame. I memorized it as a child, not knowing fully what it meant. But I do now! We only get one life on this earth…let’s make the most of each moment!)

Thank you, Mom, for always teaching me (and showing me) it is better to give than to receive.

POPPY SEED BREAD:
3 cups flour
1 1/2 t. baking powder
1 1/2 t. salt
2 1/4 cups sugar
3 eggs
1 1/2 cups milk
1 1/2 cups oil
1 1/2 T. poppy seeds
2 t. butter flavoring
2 t. vanilla
Mix together the above ingredients and beat for two minutes. 
Fill 5 or 6 mini-loaf pans 2/3 to 3/4 full. (Or I sometimes do 3 larger load pans.)
Bake at 350 for one hour. 

ORANGE GLAZE: 
3/4 cup sugar
1/4 cup orange juice
1 1/2 t. vanilla
1/2 t. butter flavoring
Mix in a glass measuring cup. Pour over hot bread when removed from the oven. Let stand for 30 minutes.

Y’all, our home’s front porch needed a little refresh, so I asked Kenny 🤠 and Dolly 👠to join me as I painted the columns, railing, and front door!  They did not disappoint! Y’all!  We painted our chicken coop and love it!! #ad
Cy built the coop last year, and I knew I would eventually want to paint it “Ebony Fields” to match my “She Shed.” So I was so excited to partner with @purdypainttools to get the job done right! 

Here are the steps we followed to paint our coop:
1.  Checked the weather forecast.
2.  Cleared the area around the coop and cleaned off any dirt or debris.
3.  Gathered paint tools. {I used the Purdy Chinex Elite brush and the Purdy Marathon roller cover in a 1/2” nap.}
4.  Painted the coop. {I used HGTV Home by SW’s Everlast paint in Ebony Fields with a satin finish!  It’s a paint and primer in one, and we only had to use ONE COAT!  Amazing!}

So easy and sooooo worth it!  Painting the coop made such a huge difference!  And of course, you know I had to decorate it a little bit. {wink}
I mean, come on!  We love our girls and want them to have a sweet home to live in.  They give us eggs...we give them a cozy little coop.  It’s a win-win!
I added some landscaping in the front and reused some old pavers we had to create walkways.  And what is a coop without a little wreath on the door, right?! 
We just love how it turned out!

Do you have an outdoor building on your property that needs a paint job to make it look brand new?  Let me know in the comments!

Now for the Cherry Limeade Recipe!🍒🥤
Ingredients: 
Bag of 8-10 limes
Large jar of maraschino cherries (reserve juice)
I/2 cup fine sugar
2 liter of lemon lime soda (I used Sprite)
DIRECTIONS:
Add nugget ice to large pitcher. 
Thinly slice a couple limes and add to pitcher. 
Drain cherries (keep juice) and add a large handful to pitcher. 
Squeeze 8 or more limes for about a cup of lime juice and add to sugar in a separate bowl. Mix well. Add lime sugar mixture to pitcher. 
Pour reserved cherry juice to pitcher. Fill pitcher with lemon lime soda and stir!  Enjoy!

Elizabeth asked me while we were painting if I really loved using Purdy brushes, which is totally a fair question! And I emphatically said, YES! They are the best! 👏🏼❤️I’ve used the cheaper kind, and I didn’t get the same smooth finish on my makeovers. 🥴

The patented lotus spikes create an acupressure massage that you can enjoy in the comfort of your own home. 🏡
There are so many other benefits, such as alleviation of headaches, boost in energy, and reduced inflammation. 
I lay on mine every night for 20 minutes, and I have seen a significant improvement in my back pain, especially when I wake up in the morning. I also like laying on my Pranamat after exercising. It definitely helps cut down on inflammation of my muscles and joints. Have you ever tried a Pranamat?  What’s your favorite way to use it?

Have you ever made these Christmas Holly Flakes? 
They are just like making Rice Krispies  treats but you use corn flakes instead of Rice Krispies, AND you add a bunch of green food coloring to your marshmallows. 
Some people will form them into wreaths, but that’s too much work for me!😂. So I just scoop them in a bunch on the parchment paper, throw some red m&m’s on them, and call it a day!👊🏼
Looks like holly to me!🤷🏻‍♀️

Here’s the recipe I used:
6 cups of corn flakes 
1 bag of mini marshmallows 
1 stick of butter 
Lots of green food coloring (I used 2 little squeeze bottles)
Parchment Paper
Red M&Ms or red hots 

Melt the marshmallows and butter together on low heat.  Add in green food coloring to desired color. Add corn flakes and stir to coat well.  Scoop mixture on parchment paper and add red M&M’s.  Let cool. Enjoy!❤️
Let me know if you’ve made these before or if you are going to try them!  They are fun and always a hit at parties!👏🏼🎄

Let’s walk into 2024 with eternity on our minds. 
When my mom had cancer, and she knew her days were numbered, she told me how everything around her looked and felt different. 
It was because she had eternity on her mind. I remember her saying it felt as if she had a pair of “eternal glasses” on her eyes, which made her see past the struggles and the heartaches, and past the temporal things that would not last, and she was able to see clearly the things that mattered most... Her relationship with Jesus, her relationship with others, and the God-given blessings all around her. 
I want to go into 2024 like my mom, with my eternal glasses on. May the plans and choices I make be in light of eternity.  Focusing on the things that outlast this life on earth. 
As we live each day, may Jesus be the desire of our hearts. 
To walk closer to him, talk more with him, spend more time in His Word, the Bible. 
Every day is one step closer to eternity with Jesus.  Knowing that gives me courage to walk into 2024 without fear. 
Trusting what I do KNOW, Jesus is with me all the way.
